body:
Hm, interesting. In https://github.com/ethereum/go-ethereum/blob/master/common/fdlimit/fdlimit_unix.go, it says
```
// Raise tries to maximize the file descriptor allowance of this process
// to the maximum hard-limit allowed by the OS.
func Raise(max uint64) error {
``` 
But in reality, it does _not_ try to set the allowance to the max allowed by the OS, but instead caps it to the `max` value provided to `Raise`. This is either an error in the docs, or implementation. I'd prefer to let the documentation remain and change the behaviour to not do anything if the os-allowance is larger than `max`.

Specifically: https://github.com/ethereum/go-ethereum/blob/c335821479db9930a98cbd48996f880c35a59797/cmd/utils/flags.go#L716 : 
```golang
func makeDatabaseHandles() int {
	if err := fdlimit.Raise(2048); err != nil {
		Fatalf("Failed to raise file descriptor allowance: %v", err)
	}
	limit, err := fdlimit.Current()
```

Should be
```golang
func makeDatabaseHandles() int {
	limit, err := getFdLimit()
	if err != nil {
		Fatalf("Failed to retrieve file descriptor allowance: %v", err)
	}
	if limit < 2048 {
		if err := raiseFdLimit(2048); err != nil{
			Fatalf("Failed to raise file descriptor allowance: %v", err)
		}
	}
```
